values: Yes...I say, everybody to the limit!

Wowie, time flies like a mofo around here.  Well, today was the last day of the beforementioned summer class.  I got an A, and that's cool.  I'm so glad it's over though.  I'm so tired of waking up at 7:30 AM, literally tired of it.  I'm going to grab a quick nap before i go to babysit.
























(Also, I'm a bad friend.)

So today marks day 1 of my new class, PSYC 341 - Group Dynamics.  It's  actually a pretty interesting class I think.  However, it's being taught by a graduate student who appears to be about 12 years of age and, this is the best part of all, is a Southern Baptist who has lived in Texas.  Oh lordy, that's the stuff of which awesomely bad jokes are made.  I can't actually think of any right now, but they'll come to me soon enough, I am sure.  Really though, he seems like a pretty cool guy, and he goes with the if-I-don't-have-my-doctorate-then-just-call-me-by-my-first-name system as so many VCU instructors.  So hoorah for not having a pole up one's arse.  Yes, yes, good, good...time for lunch!
Oh my gosh . . . awkward . . . so awkward . . . I could just swim in the sea of awkwardness.

So I went to my future brother-in-law's brother's friend's apartment.  (Phew, see if you can put that one together!)  We had so much fun!  We drank for a bit, I smoked like a freaking chimney (I know, shame on me), and then we played truth-or-dare.  Dear Lord, I haven't seen so much nudity in quite a while.  I mean a LOT of nudity, enough to go around and then some.  It was enough nudity to appease a 19-year-old boy wandering the streets of a European city, ala EuroTrip.  Well, needless to say, it was a lot of fun!  Over and out, I'm tired.
Can someone tell me what a 'suicide girl' is?  And by someone, I really mean Katie . . . Tracie and I googled it, but we couldn't quite get a grasp on what that website entailed.

Well, if you notice some of my past entries, you may notice the appearance of the name John.  There was progress tonight.  I finally got Tom to introduce us, and I actually had a conversation!  This is big, because there no longer exists a great chasm to breach when starting a conversation.  Now I can simply say, "Hello there, John!  How've you been?"  Ah, the progress I've made!  Soooooo ------> happy am I!!!

Well, Saturday was a smashing success.  Julia and Matt graduated without a hitch.  Oh, except for the fact that we, the audience, spent four hours in graduation ceremonies.  'Twas rough.  HOWEVER, I unloaded that night.  Tom and Bob had a party over at their place, and I got smashed.  I mean, six beers smashed.  Oh man, I had such a good night, because I even sobered up in time to get myself home at 3:30 AM, so I didn't have to spend the night!  

Summer school started today.  My art class (ARTE 301 - Art for the Elementary Teacher) is super fun.  We did two art projects, and that was awesome.  Then my bio lab is boring but easy.  Then English 200 shouldn't be too bad.  Not too good, but not too bad either.  I'm off to write a response paper about how my artwork pertains to the SOL's . . .
So it's 4:58, and the countdown has started.  In aproximately 32 minutes my house will be filled with the cacophony of inebriated Italian Catholics.  Pray for my soul, one and all, pray for my soul.

Well, when posting an update I try to check my spelling for accuracy.  Ocassionally, I come across a REALLY awesome mistake.  Today was one of those days, and my brain was mushy.  So I looked at a comment I was about to post and rather than the word "result," I found the word "reslut."  I'm not exactly sure what that would have meant, so I turned to Dictionary.com for answers.

re-
pref. 
Again; anew 
Backward; back 
Used as an intensive 


slut    
n. 
A woman considered sexually promiscuous. 
A woman prostitute. 
A slovenly woman; a slattern. 


So apparently a "reslut" is the following:

reslut
n.
A woman entered anew into prostitution and/or sexual promiscuity.


This tidbit has been brought to you by Jen the amazing "Miss Speller."

Well, everclear = not that bad.  I've heard horrible things about it, but it wasn't that bad.  We had three drinks, tried to go to bed, failed miserably.  So I went to the bathroom, and when I got back Katie was watching TV.
"What are you watching?...Oh!  SWEET!!!  X-FILES!!!"
A few minutes later Mandie came out and started watching too.
I think we watched three episodes...part of the Wednesday night X-Files marathon.
Well, we never went to bed, so Katie and I got cash, breakfast, and gas.  
Then I went home...so after this blow-by-blow, I'm going to bed...


.....zzzzzzzzz.....

Alrighty, I'm going for the hair appointment on Tuesday, 11 AM...soooooo excited!!!  Tracie, you're going to be the first person to see it, b/c I'm going to track you down wherever you are afterwards so you can see it and hand over your opinion.  Hopefully you won't say, "Woah, Jen, looks like someone got hit by the bleach truck."  eek!  I'm excited.  Well, my next update will probably be regarding my new hair 'do.

I have decided to remove myself from hair moritorium, the space between dark and light, and go to the light side.  I'm doing it with highlights, ala Joss Stone . . . take a look at these pictures:

Oh!  Me gusta this point in time!!!  Well, only 2 more days of classes for me, and Tracie's heading home around the sixth.  Soooooo, right now is awesome, b/c I'm happy!  Also, I have the week off from Pinchbeck next week because exams are coming up.  I mean, I love the children, but it'll be nice to have a sweet week off.  Hey, I'm only human.  

Well, Tracie and I have talked it over, and this summer shall be the summer of self-improvement for the two of us.  I already have a head start, b/c I've given up smoking.  That's good, right?  Right.  I DO miss my cloves though...mmmmmm...oh well, the occasional cloverette, as I like to call them, will not harm.  But for right now, I have neither cloves nor money by which to acquire them, so oh well.

This summer is going to involve a lot of school, but also lots of Yin/Yang time, so I cannot wait!!!

Well, over and out.

The days are getting longer.  The weather's warming up.  Lunchtime is moving out-of-doors, and people are avoiding walking through buildings to get from point A to point B.

You've got to love this sudden burst of energy that is tangible on every corner of campus.  From Temple to Hibbs from the Cricket player in Monroe Park to the rastafari-esque vender on Main Street, everything and everone is perfectly attuned to the oncoming season of Spring.

This is what I call the semester slump.  We all know the feeling.  So close, yet so far away.  Feeling like slacking off but still having too much work to make that feasible.  This is the number one worst time in the college student's life.  

All I want to do is sit outside and do nothing (maybe take a walk at the most).  I don't want to fret about the things I have left until the semester is terminated.  I don't want to care about the two biology tests, the two child psychology tests, the two English tests and two English papers, the infinite busy work from MATH 131, or the remaining exams in my dreaded Death and Dying class.  I want to chill.  Chill, chill, chill, chill, chill . . . 

P.S. I'm drunk at 6:20 in the evening.  I'm not even going out.  Goodbye, semester, goodbye.

P.P.S.  I saw a license plate yesterday that read "SNAZI."  All I could see was the plural of "Nazi" if written by someone with a bizarre form of dyslexia.

Okay, so I officially cannot wait for this semester to be over . . . Tracie, I miss you hardcore!!!  I'm just not the same without my yang!

Also, in my last summer school class (see the entry 2 below this one) Tom will be there too.  We'll carpool since he's moving to the West End with another Forneris brother (Bob).

HOORAH!

I went to David's Bridal for a bridesmaid dress fitting...

Here are a few problems with David's Bridal:

A.  One must have an appointment to try on dresses.  However, the lady assisting you doesn't do ANYTHING!

B.  I despise being called pet names by people who DON'T KNOW ME!  (i.e. sweetie, honey, or even girlfriend)

C.  The women who work there display extreme emotion at all times.  When my mom tried on a mother-of-the-bride dress that was very flattering the response was "OH!  It's just THE most beautiful dress!  You're the person that looks the best in it that I've seen!"  And when our assistant who doesn't do anything discovered we couldn't find the right top exactly (not a big deal, we order them anyway, we just try for sizes), she makes a sad puppy face and says, "Oh no!  We don't have it?!  Oh no!"   I thought she might cry.

Stupid David's Bridal, I hate thee!

Oh, I can't wait until this semester is over!  I'm having some mid-semester lethargy.  That's okay though because I have all but cemented my plans for the summer.  Of course, my evenings will be Tracie-filled (because was anyone really expecting anything else?).  Also, I'm taking summer school this go around.  I'm excited about my first class, ARTE 301 - Art for the Elementary School Teacher, because my advisor told me it's lots of arts and crafts (and I think you are all well aware of how I feel about arts and crafts!).  Buuuuuuut, I'm also taking lots of biology crap.  I'm taking the 101 lab and Human Biology and the Human Bio lab.  It won't be too fun I'm sure, but the easiest teacher is teaching it for the summer session, so that's a plus.  Altogether I'll have 8 more credits out of the way of the core requirements.  The good news is that my 101 lab only meets for 3 weeks so it will be completely and utterly bearable.  Buuuuuuut, I'll have to abandon Pinchbeck for a bit while I'm doing that, but I'll be back for the last week of school.  Eh, they'll live without me.  I need to get this semester finished the heck up!

Alright...this entry is exclusively for Tracie.  I HIGHLY approve!  The picture you sent was very telling...this may prove to be a promising situation!  I'll call you later to tell you more of what I think.

P.S.  Thanks for the music...way cool!

Sorry guys, I know my entries have been boring and about grades, but this is the last one for a while I should think.  I got a 100 on my child psyc test!  Sooooo exciting!  Yhe end . . . just wanted to share the good news.

I don't have much to say except that I finally got my grade for English!  I got a 91 (which is an A for us) and I'm sooooo happy for that.  I was freaking out about it earlier.  Well, over and out until something interesting happens.

Death...no, not the actual occurence, just the class I'm taking.  I got a 95 on the first test!  Score one for the Jennymeister!

However, I still am, unfortunately, wigging out about that friggin English test (see earlier entry regarding Dr. Kirk Richardson).  He says it takes him a week to grade the test...holy crap!

The topic?  Soup.
My comment?  Me gusta sopa.  (For you gringos, that means "I like soup.")
(Hah!  I am a gringo.)

Tracie, my dear, please pay special attention to items 6 and 15.

The weather is blah.  However, because it started snowing but didn't really stick, I got to wake up to snow falling in all its prettiness, without having to worry about wrecking my car within a half mile of my house.  BUT, I have my English test tomorrow.  I hate that class so unbelievably much, it's not even funny.  My professor has seen the Dead Poets' Society a few too many times.  All he does is show movie clips in class and tells us stories about his friend Cooper (Who, I venture to say, may be a fictional character Dr. Richardson's pulled out of his ass.).  I just feel like he's trying much too hard to impress a 200-level literature class full of 150 people and only 2 English majors.  That means that exactly 98.6(repeating)% of the class wants to write down the information needed on the tests, take the tests, pass the tests, and subsequently pass the course, thereby relinquishing him or herself from the Gen. Ed. of a 200-level English class.  But, given that he does not even lecture on American literature, I'm not sure how I am going to accomplish this.  So, wish me luck (or a meteorological catastrophe that would cause VCU to close on Friday)!

You know the breaking in period of a haircut?  Well, I've passed it.  I let my hair go curly and I'm definitely feeling it.

I had my first test in my death and dying class.  There are only three of them so the pressure was on.  I skipped all of my classes so I could study.

Watched "Wit" with Emma Thompson tonight for the class.  Great movie.  But I have a "straight crush" (as I say to describe a mild and non-sexual obsession with a member of your own sex) on Emma Thompson so I went into it slightly biased.

I had an up and down day.  But over really funny things.  Well, I wanted Moe's for dinner, but they closed at 9 and I wouldn't have enough time to go rent a video I needed for class and get over there.  So I accepted my fate of a Moe's-free evening.  Alas, I got to Blockbuster (one I usually don't rent from) and what did I behold, but a Moe's Southwestern Grill!  See down and then up!  Then, my mom told me I was going to Holland this summer and then said, "Yeah, the tickets didn't work out."  Up and then down.  
It was like VH1's Best Week Ever:
- No Moe's . . . downgrade.  Moe's next to Blockbuster . . . UPGRADE!
- Holland for two weeks . . . UPGRADE!  Tickets not working out . . . downgrade.

Oh, well.  Tomorrow I have to be at Pinchbeck in the morning.  Love the kids, hate waking up!

I'm off to bed!  I'm ready for sleep . . . 

What a wonderful day today was.  I'm happy.

Ashlee Simpson makes me laugh . . . "Ah, I'm, like, so punk!"
Correction, when I say pissed, I don't mean fuming....I actually just mean mildly annoyed.  The equivalent of muffled music from downstairs neighbors in an apartment building.

I'm truly astounded right now.  My favorite thing in the world (insert sarcasm here) is when someone does something and blames you for the same thing.  Allow me to expound.

Gabeish boy (i.e. Billy . . . Tracie, you know about the nickname) says I didn't show up for the movie.  Truth be told, I did show up.  I told him to be there a 9:30 and I left at 9:45 when he wasn't there.  Regardless, the movie began at 9:55 so he still had 10 minutes for the movie to start, but was still 15 minutes late for me.  Well, I deemed that at least midly rude.  So I told him so, to which he replies that it is rude not to have a device by which someone may reach you (i.e. a cell phone).  Well, that just about did it.  Whether he felt he was justified or not, an apology STILL would have been in order for being late for our meeting time.  Did I recieve that?  I'll give you two guesses, and the correct answer begins with an "N" and ends with an "O."

Well, I shouldn't leave out that I had Utah with me, so that was cool.
